                <p><bibl><ptr target="#beschi1970"/>, pp. <citedRange>197</citedRange> (with fig. 51), <citedRange>204</citedRange> (date of the base)</bibl>; 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#jmr1976"/>, p. 322, n. <citedRange>66</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>27.1150</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>068600</citedRange></bibl>.
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#chamoux1953"/>, pl. <citedRange>XIII, 1</citedRange> (photograph)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#belzic2022"/>, catalogue, <citedRange>B.1</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-62141"><name nymRef="#Φυλυσία">Φυλυσία</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-62046"><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Βαθυκλῆς">Βαθυκλεῦς</name></persName></persName>

	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Phylysia fille de Bathyklès.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Phylysia daughter of Bathykles.</p>
                </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Phylysia figlia di Bathykles.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                <p>The base was before World War II in Apollonia Museum (Susah) and came to Shahat only later. So it was presumably from a tomb in the Port of Cyrene.
                Upon it stood a mourning half-figure (n. 21 of Beschi's catalogue)</p>
                <p>According to <bibl><ptr target="#masson1976"/>, p. <citedRange>62</citedRange></bibl>, <foreign xml:lang="grc">Φυλυσια</foreign> should be a Libyan name.
                But the argument is not very strong and it is possible to propose a Greek origin (see <bibl><ptr target="#cdl2017"/>, p. <citedRange>486</citedRange></bibl>).</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
